  "prompt": "Are rainbows curved (bow) because raindrops are round or because the Earth surface is curved?",
  "response": "Rainbows are primarily curved (bow-shaped) due to the way light interacts with raindrops, which are spherical in shape. When sunlight enters a raindrop, it is refracted (bent), reflected off the inside surface of the droplet, and then refracted again as it exits. This process causes the light to spread out into its various colors, creating a circular arc.\n\nThe curvature you see in a rainbow is a result of this optical phenomenon and the fact that you're observing it from a specific vantage point. If you were able to see the entire circle of the rainbow, it would form a complete circle. However, the ground usually obstructs the lower half, making the arc visible from the ground look like a semi-circle.\n\nThe Earth's curvature does contribute to our perspective of rainbows, particularly when considering how rainbows appear over large distances, but the actual bow shape is primarily a result of the properties of light and the spherical shape of individual raindrops.",
